> >> >new area in compression, as many did before us.
> >> 
> >> False dichotomy.  You could compete by producing a better, cheaper
> >> product,
> 
> It seems to me you are going about this all wrong, you are never going to
> achieve decent in-roads on the non-dos market or decent user-respect unless
> you publish the source.

PKWARE has never released any sources, yet the ZIP format is very
popular. We are nevertheless working on sample sources and detailed file
format documentation.

> What you need to do is get yourself a patent. That way
> you protect your information from comercial misuse, while been able to fully
> distribute all sources. Even if you could only obtain an RSA like patent that
> was only valid in the USA and some other western countries, if your 
> product is as good as you state, then I'd imagine you would achieve great
> success. As it stands, all someone has to do is disassemble your code,
> work out the theory behind your compression, and write their own program, or
> burn their own ASIC, etc, and there is not a thing you can do about it.

We do not intend to patent the technology behind UC2.

> Get your patent application in before its too late.

We might change our mind, but I don't think that will happen.

> Julian Assange.

